responded: Good, `dom_get_doc_props_read_only` does have a null check for the document pointer at line 236. Now let me check if there's a similar pattern that should be followed when accessing the document handlers.

The problem is clear now: In the `dom_document_save_xml` function, we access `intern->document->handlers->dump_doc_to_str` and `intern->document->handlers->dump_node_to_str` without checking if `intern->document` is NULL. The document could have been freed and the pointer set to NULL by the reference counting mechanism.

The fix is to add a null check for `intern->document` before accessing its members. Let me create the patch:

args.patch:
diff --git a/ext/dom/document.c b/ext/dom/document.c
index 9650d090290..70e398dd50c 100644
--- a/ext/dom/document.c
+++ b/ext/dom/document.c
@@ -1616,6 +1616,11 @@ static void dom_document_save_xml(INTERNAL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS, zend_class_entry

 	DOM_GET_OBJ(docp, ZEND_THIS, xmlDocPtr, intern);

+	if (intern->document == NULL) {
+		php_error_docref(NULL, E_WARNING, "Invalid state: document has been destroyed");
+		RETURN_FALSE;
+	}
+
 	libxml_doc_props const* doc_props = dom_get_doc_props_read_only(intern->document);
 	bool format = doc_props->formatoutput;

@@ -1624,6 +1629,10 @@ static void dom_document_save_xml(INTERNAL_FUNCTION_PARAMETERS, zend_class_entry
 		/* Dump contents of Node */
 		DOM_GET_OBJ(node, nodep, xmlNodePtr, nodeobj);
 		if (node->doc != docp) {
+			if (intern->document == NULL) {
+				php_error_docref(NULL, E_WARNING, "Invalid state: document has been destroyed");
+				RETURN_FALSE;
+			}
 			php_dom_throw_error(WRONG_DOCUMENT_ERR, dom_get_strict_error(intern->document));
 			RETURN_FALSE;
